"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Talcott_(military_officer)","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"politics","header":"He was named guardian of the charter","body":"When Connecticut's royal charter arrived from Charles the Second in 1662, the freemen chose Talcott, with Samuel Wyllys and Lieutenant John Allyn, as the committee sworn to keep it in their custody. A quarter-century later he would help spirit that same charter away from Andros.","number":1},{"category":"politics","header":"He took the charter as the candles died","body":"By Roger Wolcott's 1764 account, when the candles were snuffed in the Hartford meeting-house in 1687, Talcott and Nathaniel Stanley lifted the two colonial charters from the table before Andros could seize them. Wolcott's telling names no oak; the tree entered the tradition later, and the duplicate passed to his son-in-law Joseph Wadsworth.","number":2},{"category":"military","header":"Connecticut's victorious commander in King Philip's War","body":"Talcott led Connecticut's forces through King Philip's War in 1675 and 1676, winning a string of engagements that earned him promotion to lieutenant-colonel. His campaigns ranged from the river towns down into the Narragansett country.","number":3},{"category":"politics","header":"He kept the colony's purse for sixteen years","body":"Talcott served as treasurer of Connecticut Colony from 1660 to 1676, taking the office directly from his father before him. The family's account books became a running ledger of early Hartford.","number":4},{"category":"death","header":"He died intestate, his estate worth thousands","body":"Talcott died in 1688 without a will, leaving an estate appraised at more than two thousand pounds, a substantial colonial fortune. It passed by primogeniture to his eldest surviving son, the future governor Joseph Talcott.","number":5}],"military_service":[{"war":"King Philip's War","active_in_war":true,"rank":"Lieutenant Colonel","dates":"1676"